TY  - JOUR
AU  - Diamond, Douglas W.
T1  - Financial Intermediation and Delegated Monitoring
PY  - 1984
Y1  - 1984/07/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297430
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 51
IS  - 3
SP  - 393
EP  - 414
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This paper develops a theory of financial intermediation based on minimizing the cost of monitoring information which is useful for resolving incentive problems between borrowers and lenders. It presents a characterization of the costs of providing incentives for delegated monitoring by a financial intermediary. Diversification within an intermediary serves to reduce these costs, even in a risk neutral economy. The paper presents some more general analysis of the effect of diversification on resolving incentive problems. In the environment assumed in the model, debt contracts with costly bankruptcy are shown to be optimal. The analysis has implications for the portfolio structure and capital structure of intermediaries.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297430
ER  - 



